Meeting Opener
 
We discussed the goals of the landing pages, from making sure they are released as soon as possible and adapting the pages to fit the marketing criteria set by the team in order to sell and allow growth as much as possible. The website and landing pages require quick performance to entice users, and we need to use next.JS components to achieve a quicker release process by removing any production delays such as needing to change the content and ensuring the dismissal of the developer's role in the change as they have higher priorities. The stakeholders in this meeting should also be aligned on what to do next.  
 
Agenda
 
1- Discussing where the team has reached so far in the production process, which was as follows: 
 
The first prototype of the education landing page revealed some technical issues, such as components with dirty code that doesn't allow change in the designs (components break with a singular, simple change). Components are not created equal. The development and testing phases have been completed, and the page is set to be released today 31/07/2024.

2- Discussion of the terminology of the next.JS building structures as Serag presented.
 
3- Discussing how the components we used for the first prototype was not the best, flexiwind components had the cleanest code.

4- Revealing that Schadcn was reliable but not built to suit our needs in the landing pages. It was purely atomics and components, no higher level sections or pages. They are also best suited for dashboards, not landing pages. 

5- Discussion of how to reach a codebase with reliable higher level items. 

6- We discussed how the designers in the meeting will rely on figma even though it doesn't offer the direct translation we need from component library to design. For now, we have to use HTML to figma. 

7- Discussion of how Directus has no visual builder. 

8- Discussion of how Framer has no self-hosting, which makes us doubtful of using it for Framer Motion animations.

9- Comparing Plasmic web builder to Webbuilder in features. We also discussed the possibility of creating our own visual builder or consider trying out Plasmic for a few months until we can adapt our own builder.

10- Consider researching Payload. It is developer centered so there is doubt whether it is easy for the designers to use.

Conclusion and Action Plan

1- Release the first landing page prototype even if it's not ideal, whilst Serag and Sara work on creating a component library using the better components that have clean code for future use.

2- Study and research Payload to see if it's a viable open-source web building alternative.

3- Amira will give feedback via heatmaps and statistics when the new landing page is released for future design improvements.

SUNDAY 4/08: LMS content will be done.
